                <div class="div-line"></div>
                
                <h2 class="subheading">Overview & Positioning</h2>

                <h3 class="subheading">Maruti Swift</h3>
                <p>Launched in India on 9 May 2024 (new fourth-generation), the Swift is a sporty, compact hatchback built on Suzuki's HEARTECT platform. It targets buyers looking for a peppy, stylish city car with strong fuel efficiency, and it retains the hatchback charm that made earlier generations successful.</p>

                <h3 class="subheading">Tata Punch</h3>
                <p>Produced since 2021, the Punch is a crossover-city car (A/B-segment SUV) positioned as Tata's smallest "SUV". Built on the ALFA-ARC platform shared with the Altroz, it blends rugged SUV styling with city-car practicality. The Punch often appeals to those wanting SUV attributes in a compact package.</p>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">Engine & Performance</h2>

                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table class="comparison-table-content">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th class="text-center">Specification</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Maruti Swift (Z12E Petrol)</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Tata Punch (Revotron 1.2 I3 Petrol)</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Displacement</td>
                                <td>1,197 cc, 3-cylinder Z12E</td>
                                <td>1,199 cc, 3-cylinder Revotron</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Power</td>
                                <td>~80 PS@5,700 rpm</td>
                                <td>87.8 PS@6,000 rpm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Torque</td>
                                <td>112 Nm@4,500 rpm</td>
                                <td>115 Nm@3,250 rpm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Transmission</td>
                                <td>5-speed manual, 5-speed AMT (AGS), CVT</td>
                                <td>5-speed manual, 5-speed AMT</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <p><span class="font-weight-700">Takeaway:</span> Both have near-identical engine sizes and power figures, but the Punch offers more torque at lower RPM, potentially providing better low-end response.</p>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">Fuel Efficiency</h2>

